<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">
You're reading messages from people who have misread and misinterpreted the patch statement, and as a consequence are seeing gremlins where none exist.<P>The patch message said something to the effect that MOBs are now aware of a players vulnerability (or, rather, their <B>invulnerability</B>), and will be less likely to attack invulnerable players.<P>The meaning of "invulnerable" in this context is "cannot be harmed <I>at all</I>".  There are a number of spells that provide complete invulnerability to the target.  The Shieldskin spell of wizards makes them immune to damage until the Shieldskin is broken through.  The Divine Aura spell for Clerics makes them completely immune to all forms of damage for 18 seconds.  The 60th level Bard song gives a Divine Aura effect to the Bard's entire party for 18 seconds.  Necros also have a spell that completely negates all damage from any source.<P>THIS is what the patch message means by "invulnerability": Players who cannot be harmed <I>at all</I>.<P>Players that can take damage aren't affected by the change.  The change doesn't make MOBs ignore characters who are <I>more difficult</I> to harm (i.e. characters with high AC and HP).  If none of these spells which completely negate damage are cast, the MOB will behave like always.  If any of these spells <I>are</I> cast, whoever receives the benefits of the spell will drop to the bottom of the hate list.<P>And that's all the change is.    <IMG SRC="biggrin.gif" border="0"><P>--------------------<P> <IMG SRC="http://www.erols.com/aburner/eq/ruathasig.gif"> <BR>51st Level Gnome Championette<BR><I>WARNING!  I am a professional test gnome using special test equipment on a closed stunt server.  DO NOT TRY THIS AT HOME!</I>
</FONT>
